## Test Anti-Pattern Audit — `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**This is a textbook coverage-touching test class.** All 10 public methods are called — hitting the 95% coverage number — but almost nothing is actually verified. You have the illusion of a safety net with almost none of the protection.

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| Critical | 6 |
| High | 0 |
| Medium | 2 |
| Low | 1 |

---

### Critical — False Confidence

#### 1. Coverage Touching (Systemic)

The entire class systematically calls every method on `ProductCatalog` in declaration order with no meaningful assertions. This is the classic "touch every method for coverage stats" pattern.

**Tests with zero assertions:**

| Method | Line | Problem |
|--------|------|---------|
| `AddProduct_Works` | 17–21 | No assertion. Could silently corrupt data. |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` | 31–36 | Calls update, never checks the price changed. |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` | 38–43 | Calls remove, never checks product is gone. |
| `GetProductCount_Works` | 63–66 | Discards the return value entirely. |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` | 68–74 | Never checks any prices were reduced. |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` | 84–88 | Never checks anything was imported. |

#### 2. Trivial `IsNotNull` Assertions Masquerading as Verification

| Method | Line | Problem |
|--------|------|---------|
| `GetProduct_Works` | 28 | Asserts result is not null but never checks SKU, name, or price are correct. A method that returns `new Product("", "", 0)` would pass. |
| `SearchProducts_Works` | 51 | Asserts results collection is not null — never checks it contains the right product or excludes the wrong one. |
| `GetAllProducts_Works` | 59 | Same — doesn't check count or contents. |
| `ExportToCsv_Works` | 81 | Asserts CSV string is not null — never checks format, values, or content. |

---

### Concrete Fixes (Before → After)

**`AddProduct_Works` → verify round-trip:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_StoresProductRetrievableBySku()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);

    var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
}
```

**`UpdatePrice_Works` → verify price actually changed:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_ChangesStoredPrice()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);

    var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated?.Price);
}
```

**`RemoveProduct_Works` → verify product is gone:**
```csharp
[TestMethod]
